4: I seem to have eluded them...
11:
Why does the Aegis Squadron
continue this pursuit? As
Commander, I reject the judgment
of the Squadron—
13:
You stand accused of attempting to
access forbidden memory bytes.
15:
What you intended to do with the
memories of that defunct squadron
unit I do not know. But you must be
aware that you broke the law.
16:
Our duty is to uphold law and order.
That the First Commander of the
Aegis Squadron would transgress in
such a way is unacceptable.
28:
Your power is extraordinary. 
But there is no place for you to run.
34:
A secret room… Its existence was
completely erased from all data
sources.
36:
To what end did the Administrator
hide such an object here?
45:
Indeed, I may linger yet a while
longer.
47:
Your idle curiosity has always gotten
the better of you.
50:
A recreation of a long-lost facility
once common in human civilization.
What was the nomenclature? A
library?
52:
Quite peculiar that they would go
out of their way to externalize
archives by imprinting them onto
this substance called paper…
54:
Heh, you know some droids these
days—mostly radicals, mind
you—say there's no point in
archiving data. Not when you can
just store it directly in your memory.
56:
But that's neither here nor there.
Take a look at this, Sera.
58:
Beautiful, isn't it?
It's a blue flower that once existed,
long ago.
59:
They say that every flower has a
name—an abstract concept that
they represent. Like how roses
symbolize love.
61:
...I fail to understand. A flower is a
flower.
64:
Not a single romantic module in
your body, is there? This flower
reminds me of you—I should like to
give it a fitting name.
66:
In that case, please hasten your
consideration. We have precious
little time on leave.
74:
And you found her unconscious in
the square, you say?
77:
Yes. I tried speaking to her, but she
did not respond.
81:
You did well bringin' her here. She's
one of them droids, ain't she?
82:
None of our medicine's gonna work
on her, huh.
86:
It might be better to go look for
someone who can help.
93:
My apologies. It seems I have
caused you a great inconvenience.
99:
We are in Starview Village—a
location that serves as the
intersection of many worlds.
112:
Suspicious unidentified autonomous
lifeform identified! Commencing
extermination procedures.
122:
Lifeform is… extremely soft, snuggly,
and fluffy… Compliance with
extermination order proving to be
difficult... Must maintain public order,
but target is... so cute...
130:
Light is indeed a very fluffy and soft
lifeform. But he is also our dear
friend.
132:
You can't exterminate him. Please
let him go.
137: Have I... made an error in judgment?
143: Nice of you to notice… Oww…
149:
I am sorry for the commotion I
caused.
152:
So, you were saying that this is an
entirely different world?
154:
And Commander Light here is
actually your leader? Please forgive
me for my brash and disrespectful
actions, Sir!
157:
I suppose your response was
understandable, given you had just
woken up and were no doubt quite
confused…
158:
…Though I fear you may have
misjudged the situation yet again.
162:
So, you gonna tell us why the hell
you were lying out there in such bad
shape?
169:
I am currently on a very important
mission to search for a key suspect.
172:
In other words, you're on an
investigation?
175:
Yes. The information is highly
classified, so I cannot divulge more.
However, I can say that they are
guilty of disturbing the peace.
180:
You think it's possible it could be
that rust bucket?
185:
Let's not jump to any conclusions. I
mean, every single one of us fits a
description like that.
189:
Let us set the matter aside for now.
Welcome to Starview Village, Sera.
194: I am free to stay here?
199:
Of course. At the very least until your
wounds heal.
200:
If you require assistance, let us
know. We have allies on the Android
Planet as well, should you need
them.
205:
As soon as I recover I will endeavor
to lend my aid to the people of
Starview Village under your
guidance, Commander!
208:
I must emphasize that I am NOT the
commander here…
